Exercise for Lecture 5 - more on differential expression with the limma package

library(limma)
library(ggplot2)
library(reshape2)
library(ggforce)
library(dplyr)
library(plotROC)
library(matrixStats)
nGenes <- 10000                   # number of "features"
nSamples <- 6                     # number of samples (split equal in 2 groups)
pDiff <- .1                       # percent of genes "differential 
grp <- rep(0:1,each=nSamples/2)   # dummy variable for exp. group
trueFC <- 2                       # log-fold-change of truly DE

d0 <- 1
s0 <- 0.8
sd <- s0*sqrt(d0/rchisq(nGenes,df=d0))  # dist'n of s.d.
y <- matrix(rnorm(nGenes*nSamples,sd=sd),
            nr=nGenes,nc=nSamples)
indD <- 1:floor(pDiff*nGenes)
diff <- rep(0, nrow(y))
diff[indD] <- sample(c(-1,1),max(indD),replace=TRUE)*trueFC
table(diff)
## diff
##   -2    0    2 
##  475 9000  525
y[,grp==1] <- y[,grp==1] + diff

Question 1. First, do an exploratory analysis of the true and observed variances. For the observed variances, compute the residual variance for each row of y (i.e., pooled variance of the two simulated samples, not the row-wise variance; see the denominator of the classical two-sample t-statistic) and look at the distribution of them, of the true variances (from the simulated sd) and a scatter plot of true versus observed. Sometimes viewing variances on the log scale is preferred.

rvars <- (rowVars(y[,grp==1]) + rowVars(y[,grp==0]))/2
variance <- rep(c("true","observed"), each=nGenes)

qplot(c(sd^2,rvars), geom="density", colour = variance) +
  scale_x_log10()

# average below because both groups are same size
# otherwise, it would be weighted by n_1-1, n_2-1
qplot(sd^2, rvars) + geom_point() + 
  scale_x_log10() + scale_y_log10() +
  geom_density_2d(col="yellow") +
  geom_abline(slope=1, intercept=0, col="blue")

Question 3. In terms of the model that is fit for each feature, what is the interpretation of the two columns of this design matrix?

(design <- model.matrix(~grp))
##   (Intercept) grp

The first column represents the intercept term and the second column represents the change in expression between the two groups.

fit <- lmFit(y,design)
fit <- eBayes(fit)

Question 4. For each row of y, calculate also the classical 2-sample t-test. See ?t.test for more details about the built-in R function to do this calculation and convince yourself which arguments to use to match the classical t-test described in class. Add a visualization similar to the above plot for the classical t-statistic and the log-fold-change (mean difference). Which statistic best separates the truly differential from non-differential?

The easiest way to do this is from the summaries in the limma output - t.test(.,var.equal=TRUE) can do the same thing:

# object contain 
classical_t <- fit$coef[,2]/fit$sigma/fit$stdev.unscaled[,2]
stats <- data.frame(moderated_t = fit$t[,2],
                    classical_t,
                    log_fold_change = fit$coef[,2], 
                    diff = as.factor(diff))

m <- melt(stats)
## Using diff as id variables
m$index <- seq_len(length(classical_t))

ggplot(m, aes(x=diff, y=value)) + geom_violin() + 
  facet_grid(~variable) + ylim(-6,6)
## Warning: Removed 870 rows containing non-finite values (stat_ydensity).

ggplot(m, aes(x=index, y=value, colour=diff)) + geom_point(size=.4) + 
  facet_wrap(~variable, ncol=1) + ylim(-6,6)
## Warning: Removed 870 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Question 5. Pick a reasonable metric to compare the methods, such as an ROC curve, false discovery plot, power versus achieved FDR. Using this metric/curve, formally compare the classical t-test, the moderated t-test and the log-fold-change or mean difference (fit$coef). Two packages that are useful for these kind of plots include: https://rocr.bioinf.mpi-sb.mpg.de/ or https://bioconductor.org/packages/release/bioc/html/iCOBRA.html.

There are many choices, but an ROC curve is one reasonable choice:

ggplot(m, aes(m = abs(value), d = !(diff==0), colour=variable)) + geom_roc()

Question 6. From the matrix of summarized Affymetrix data that went into the limma pipeline in the first place (exprs(eset)), manually calculate the logFC and AveExpr for one of the top differentially expressed features.

As an example, I use fit2 and coef=2, which represents the contrast present48-absent48:

tt <- topTable(fit2,coef=2)[1,]
tt
##           logFC  AveExpr        t      P.Value    adj.P.Val        B
## 910_at 3.855061 9.660238 29.20918 8.266125e-10 1.043598e-05 11.60619
thise <- exprs(eset)[rownames(tt),]

mean(thise)  # AveExpr
## [1] 9.660238
mean(thise[f=="present48"])-mean(thise[f=="absent48"])  # logFC
## [1] 3.855061
